-- Ghana Cocoa Buying From Farmers Rises 45% in Season so Far
-- B y   M o s e s   M o z a r t   D z a w u
-- 2011-02-04T09:51:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-04/ghana-cocoa-buying-from-farmers-rises-45-in-season-so-far-official-says.html
Cocoa purchases in  Ghana , the world’s
second-largest producer of the beans, increased 45 percent in
the first 16 weeks of the marketing season, according to a
government official with access to the information.  Companies licensed by The  Ghana  Cocoa Board to purchase the
beans from farmers bought 664,498 metric tons in the period
ended Jan. 20, compared with 458,200 tons in the same period a
year earlier, the data showed. The official declined to be
identified because the figures are confidential.  Purchases during the week ended Jan. 20 increased to 21,252
tons from 18,903 tons in the 16th week of the 2009-10 season,
the data showed. Ghana borders  Ivory Coast , the world’s biggest
producer of the chocolate ingredient.  Cocoa for March delivery fell 1.1 percent to 2,168 pounds
($3,499) a ton as of 9:47 a.m. London time, paring its gain so
far this year to 7.4 percent.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Antony Sguazzin at 
 asguazzin@bloomberg.net . 